<p><ent>Peal</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Peal
<hw>Peal</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[An abbrev. of F. <ets>appel</ets> a
call, appeal, ruffle of a drum, fr. <ets>appeller</ets> to call, L.
<ets>appellare</ets>. See <er>Appeal</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
loud sound, or a succession of loud sounds, as of bells, thunder,
cannon, shouts, of a multitude, etc.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧A fair <xex>peal</xex>
of artillery.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Hayward.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whether those <qex>peals</qex> of praise be his or no.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And a deep thunder, <qex>peal</qex> on <qex>peal</qex>, afar.</q>
<rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A set of bells tuned to each other according to the
diatonic scale; also, the changes rung on a set of bells.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To ring a peal</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Ring</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Peal</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Peal
<hw>Peal</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Pealed</conjf> <pr>(p⟦emac⟧ld)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Pealing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To utter or give out
loud sounds.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There let the <qex>pealing</qex> organ blow.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To resound; to echo.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And the whole air <qex>pealed</qex>⟦br⟧
<qex>With the cheers of our men</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Peal</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Peal
<hw>Peal</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To utter or give forth
loudly; to cause to give out loud sounds; to noise abroad.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The warrior's name,⟦br⟧
Though <qex>pealed</qex> and chimed on all the tongues of fame.</q>
<rj><qau>J. Barlow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To assail with noise or loud sounds.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nor was his ear less <qex>pealed</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To pour out.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>
<rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>peal out</ent>⟦br⟧
